{"id":"1603.07708","submitter":"Fred Diamond","authors":"Lassina Dembele, Fred Diamond, David P. Roberts","title":"Serre weights and wild ramification in two-dimensional Galois\n  representations","comments":"Revised version, including reference to above-mentioned proof\n  (arXiv:1608.06059)","journal-ref":"Forum Math. Sigma 4 (2016), e33, 49 pp","doi":"10.1017/fms.2016.27","report-no":null,"categories":"math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A generalization of Serre's Conjecture asserts that if $F$ is a totally real\nfield, then certain characteristic $p$ representations of Galois groups over\n$F$ arise from Hilbert modular forms. Moreover it predicts the set of weights\nof such forms in terms of the local behavior of the Galois representation at\nprimes over $p$. This characterization of the weights, which is formulated\nusing $p$-adic Hodge theory, is known under mild technical hypotheses if $p >\n2$. In this paper we give, under the assumption that $p$ is unramified in $F$,\na conjectural alternative description for the set of weights. Our approach is\nto use the Artin-Hasse exponential and local class field theory to construct\nbases for local Galois cohomology spaces in terms of which we identify\nsubspaces that should correspond to ones defined using $p$-adic Hodge theory.\nThe resulting conjecture amounts to an explicit description of wild\nramification in reductions of certain crystalline Galois representations. It\nenables the direct computation of the set of Serre weights of a Galois\nrepresentation, which we illustrate with numerical examples. A proof of this\nconjecture has been announced by Calegari, Emerton, Gee and Mavrides.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 24 Mar 2016 18:59:46 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sun, 2 Oct 2016 09:40:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-12-13"}
